fields: Definition: self-regulating process for biological systems to maintain stability while adjusting to optimal conditions for survival

low/reduce/dampen processes vs. positive feedback loops accelerate processes or increase output 
- Most biological systems = negative feedback loops to self-stabilize, e.g. BP regulation, HR, temperature control
Describe a homeostatic process in the human body. Give specific examples of how all the organs work together.

Body temperature control at 37C 
- Temperature regulation controlled by hypothalamus in brain → changes due to exposure, hormonal changes, metabolic rate changes, disease states → compensatory mechanisms e.g. shunting of blood to skin or core, sweating, shivering 
- Stimulus (temp change) → Receptors (in skin and brain) → control center (thermoregulation in brain) → effectors (sweat if hot, shivering in skeletal muscles if cold)
Describe how dysfunction in a single organ can lead to dysfunction of another organ.

Heat stroke example leading to multiple organ dysfunction syndrome (MODS) - Excess sweating → low blood volume → heart can’t pump as well b/c lacks volume → 
less blood to lungs for oxygenation → organs receive less oxygen → organs begin to fail, e.g. muscle breakdown causing rhabdomyolysis → damaged muscle releases toxins that damage the heart and kidneys; lack of blood in GI tract → bacterial infection → sepsis
List the steps associated in the loss of homeostasis in heat stroke.

Heat rash
Heat cramps
Heat exhaustion
Heat stroke

- Increased blood flow to skin to help cool pulls blood away from GI → stomach cramps 
- Loss of body salts → electrolyte imbalance → cramps in hands, calves, feet + hard, tense muscles
Profuse sweating causes body salt and fluid loss (decreased blood volume) → dizziness, headache, nausea, weakness, irritability, orthostatic hypotension

-Core body temperature rises → CNS dysfunction, coma, death 
- Do NOT give fluids before checking salt balance - change in electrolyte balance due to sweat (water and salts get sweated out)
Describe and demonstrate standard anatomical position
Standing, looking forward, arms down to the side, palms facing forward, legs parallel, toes facing forward
Describe the planes of anatomical section

Sagittal: left to right, side to side 
- Median plane: divides down the middle 
- Parasagittal: all other sagittal planes (not middle) 
- Transverse/axial: top to bottom 
- Frontal/coronal: front to back
Apply the planes of anatomical section to medical imaging

- CT and MRI give 2D slices in any section of 3D information & can be rendered in 3D models
- Transverse CT is usually inferior view (looking from feet to head) but neurology scans are usually superior (top of head down to feet)
Apply the planes of anatomical section to medical imaging
Ultrasound also 2D slices of 3D; usually transverse or sagittal plane but can image any true or oblique plane via position of transponder

-  {{c1::anterior/ventral}} (front) vs. {{c1::posterior/dorsal}} (back)
-  {{c1::rostral}} (closer to nose) vs. {{c1::caudal}} (back of head) - for head/brain
-  {{c1::superior/cranial}} (closer to head) vs. i{{c1::nferior/caudal}} (closer to foot)
-  {{c1::medial}} (median) vs. l{{c1::ateral}} (further from median)
- {{c1:: proximal}} (closer to trunk or origin) vs. {{c1::distal}} (further from trunk or origin) - for limbs and 
linear structures
-  {{c1::dorsum}} (superior part of body protrusions e.g. back of/posterior hand or top of/superior
foot) vs. {{c1::palmar}} (palm/anterior hand) vs. plantar (sole/inferior foot)
-  {{c1::deep}} (closest to core) vs. {{c1::superficial}} (closest to surface) vs. intermediate (in between)
-  {{c1::external}} (further from core) vs. {{c1::internal}} (closer to core)
-  {{c1::unilateral}} (only one side) vs. {{c1::bilateral}} (paired in left/right, both sides)
-  {{c1::contralateral}} (opposite side) vs. {{c1::ipsilateral}} (same side)
Describe the contents of a nerve, including afferent and efferent components

{{c1::Nerves}} are bundle of axons, both sensory and motor, arranged in sequential bundles
wrapped in myelin and supportive glial cells
- Often associated with blood vessels wrapped in fat/fascia to form neurovascular bundles
{{c1::Axons}} can deliver signals to/from brain/spinal cord to/from target - motor (brain to target) vs. sensory (target to brain)

- Most nerves (except some from the brain) are both motor and sensory, though 
some terminal branches of nerves might have primarily sensory components
Explain the clinical relevance of spinal cord segments, dermatome, myotome, peripheral nerve territories, and referred pain.
Spinal cord segments allow for localization of spinal cord problems based on location and symptoms/signs
{{c1::Cranial nerves (12 pairs)}} have specific functions - motor, sensory, or both
{{c1::Spinal nerves (31 pairs)}} are always both motor and sensory
Cervical ({{c1::8}}), thoracic ({{c1::12}}), lumbar ({{c1::5}}), sacral/coccygeal ({{c1::6}}) → cervical plexus, brachial plexus, intercostal nerves, lumbar plexus, sacral plexus
{{c1::Dermatome}}: all skin innervated by that spinal nerve on that side
{{c1::Myotome}}: all muscles innervated by that spinal nerve on that side
{{c1::Peripheral}} nerve territories: do not directly match dermatomes/myotomes
4 regions where anterior rami (spinal nerve branches) recombine called plexus of nerves: {{c1::cervical, brachial, lumbar, sacral }}
{{c1::Referred pain}}: pain on a part of the body wall that refers back to a specific organ b/c of cross-talk between sensory neurons from organs and from external body

- Somatic PNS: can control (muscles, bones, body wall) 
- Afferent (sensory): from body to CNS, e.g. pain, touch 
- Efferent (motor): CNS to body, e.g. conscious/reflexive control of muscle - Visceral PNS: autonomic (organs) 
- Efferent (motor) for homeostasis 
- Parasympathetic (rest & digest) from cranial and sacral nerves for 
vasodilation in gut, lower HR, etc. 
- Sympathetic (fight or flight) from thoracic and lumbar nerves for 
vasoconstriction in gut, sweating, etc.
{{c1::Arteries}}: away from heart, thick smooth muscle and elastic fibers for high pressure

{{c1::Veins}}: towards heart, valves to prevent backflow, thinner smooth muscle for lower
pressures

{{c1::Neurovascular bundles:}} arteries, veins, and nerves run in parallel enclosed by a
fascial/vascular sheath
Flow of blood: {{c1::IVC/SVC → RA → tricuspid valve → RV → pulmonary valve → pulmonary arteries → lungs → pulmonary veins → LA → mitral valve → LV → aortic valve → aorta }}
Explain the clinical relevance of anastomosis, collateral circulation, venous drainage, and lymphatic drainage

Anastomosis interconnections of arteries and veins for incr. blood flow or detours, e.g. if one vessel is constricted or compressed and blood flow is critical i.e. collateral circulation 
Venous drainage: superficial veins from skin → deep veins surrounded by muscle

-  Venous drainage via muscle contractions and valves for unidirectional flow
-  Anastomoses for redundant drainage
connective tissue under skin to protect/support muscles and organs - Superficial fascia includes fat and loose connective tissue
{{c1::Deep}} fascia is tough, mostly tendinous dense regular connective tissue, no fat - Overlies muscles and varies in thickness

{{c1:: Bursa}}: sacs of connective tissue with serous fluid around mobile structures to lubricate and protect, e.g. tendons, heart, lungs 
-{{c1::Parietal layer}}: outside on body wall, e.g. chest cavity wall 
- {{c1::Synovial}}: fluid-filled, lubricating 
- {{c1::Visceral layer}}: against organ
{{c1::Potential space}} from separation of parietal and visceral layers; pathologic or due to clinical intervention, e.g. aortic dissection
. Describe how relationships between organ systems can be used to organize knowledge in a somatic example (muscular compartment) and a visceral example (small intestine)

Somatic example: myofascial compartment 
- Somatic systems are in layers of muscle and fascia 
- Myofascial compartment: layers of muscle surrounded by connective tissue with neurovasculature (arteries, veins, nerves) 
- Many muscles in compartments are innervated by a small number of nerves and often share common functional roles 
- Visceral example: small intestine 
- Mesentery (fascia/connective tissue) with blood vessels, lymphatics, nerves innervate small intestine organ - visceral/autonomic motor (efferent) or visceral sensation (afferent) 
- Blood supply and nervous supply segmental, e.g. superior abdomen from celiac trunk of aorta

- Patient: specific, but not too specific 
- Intervention: risk/preventative factors, therapies, diagnostic tests 
- Comparison/Control: alternative to intervention, e.g. gold standard or placebo - - Outcome: endpoint that is clinically relevant to patient
Identify the four steps of the practice of EBM. - 4 A’s

- Ask: pt-centered clinical questions 
- Acquire: evidence 
- Appraise: evaluate evidence → conclusion 
        *  Validity (internal vs. external vs. construct) 
- Apply: apply evidence to clinical question for patient’s goals
Order of increasing quality of information
Background info/expert opinion → case series/reports → case control studies → cohort studies → randomized controlled trials → systematic reviews → meta-analysis
Describe the three basic competencies in pathology

(1) understand core principles of disease mechanisms/processes - general pathology, e.g. cell injury/death/adaptations, inflammation/repair (acute and chronic), hemodynamic disorders/shock, immunological diseases, neoplasia (new unregulated growth), pediatric/genetic, environmental/nutritional 
- (2) apply knowledge of disease mechanisms to organ systems, e.g. clinical presentation, untreated history of disease, likely treatment outcomes 
- (3) apply general and system path to diagnostic medicine, e.g. lab/imaging studies
Describe the approach used in the diagnosis of neoplasms and other pathologies, including the use of tumor markers.

- Tissue sampling methods: needle aspiration, biopsies, smears etc. 
- Subtype/tissue of origin (use IHC, flow, molecular/genetic studies) & prognostic info (grade, stage, margins) 
- Tumor markers (enzymes, hormones, other - e.g. specific antigens) in blood or bodily fluid → tumor screening, dx, prognostic indicators, monitoring outcome
{{c1::Genotype}} (genetic) vs. {{c1::phenotype}} (observable, either dominant or recessive)
alternative forms of a gene at that locus - WT vs. mutant
{{c1::Homozygote}} (2 identical alleles at locus) vs. {{c1::heterozygote}} (2 different alleles at locus) vs. {{c1::hemizygote}} (1 allele at locus)
phenotype caused by diff mutations at the same locus
phenotype from mutations at 2+ separate loci
{{c1::Variable expression}}: same genotype → different phenotypes, e.g. neurofibromatosis
{{c1::Pleiotropy:}} multiple effects by one gene, e.g. Marfan → multiple organ systems

{{c1::Reduced penetrance}}: proportion (below) reduced if people with the genotype/variant do 
not have the disorder, esp in autosomal dominant conditions

{{c1::Penetrance}} = # individuals with genotype with disorder / total # individuals with 
genotype
{{c1::Consanguinity:}} related couples who are second cousins or closer
{{c1::Copy number variant}} (CNV): part of genome is duplicated, opposite of a deletion
{{c1::Pedigree:}} chart that diagrams the inheritance of a trait or health condition through generations of a family
{{c1:: Autosomal dominant}}: traits expressed in heterozygote or homozygote

- Phenotype appears in every generation 
- Any child of affected parent has 50% chance of inheriting 
- Phenotypically normal members don’t transmit trait to children 
- Male/female equally likely
{{c1::Autosomal recessive}}: less common, only expressed in homozygote

Appears only in sibship (same two parents) of proband (starting point of genetic study) 
- Recurrence for siblings of affected individuals is 1 in 4. If sibling is unaffected, sibling has 2 in 3 chance of being a heterozygous carrier 
- Parents sometimes consanguineous, esp in rare recessive disorders 
- Parents of affected person are asymptomatic carriers of mutant allele 
- Male/female equally likely

{{c1::Lyon hypothesis}}: in female somatic cells, only one X is active, the other X is inactivated/condensed early in embryonic development called a Barr body - Inactive X can either be paternal or maternal, but all descendents will be the same - Dosage compensation (female only express 1 allele of X-linked gene, but have 2) and variable expression in female heterozygotes

- X-inactivation is random so some will have paternal X active in half of cells and maternal X active in half of cells → variable expression → diff 
severity of phenotype
{{c1::X-linked recessive}}, e.g. hemophilia A and Duchenne muscular dystrophy

- Higher incidence in males 
- Male offspring of carrier female - 50% affected vs. female offspring 50% carrier - Mutant gene transmitted from man to all daughters (b/c gives X) 
- Mutant gene never transmitted from father to son (b/c gives Y) 
- Affected males related through females 
- Heterozygous females usually unaffected, but can have variable expression

- Affected males has no affected sons, only affected daughters (no normal) 
- Both male and female offspring of heterozygous female have 50% affected 
- Affected females 2x more common than affected males, but usually milder expression due to Lyonization 
- For prenatal lethal in hemizygous males, sex ratio offspring of heterozygous mothers is 2:1 female b/c affected males spontaneously aborted
Understand the mechanisms of pedigree formation, including limitations in the current standard process
Advanced reproductive technology (ART), e.g. sperm donation, IVF, etc. - LGBTQ+ supportive language/approach, e.g. domestic partnerships, gender affirmation
Autocrine: receptors and signaling on same cell (self), e.g. cytokines by TH cells → TH cell upregulation
ligand (signaling cell) -receptor (target cell) direct binding, e.g. T cell binding antigen presenting cells
{{c1::Juxtacrine}}: ligand (signaling cell) -receptor (target cell) direct binding, e.g. T cell binding antigen presenting cells
{{c1::Paracrine}}: adjacent cells, distant effects, e.g. cytokines by TH cells → upregulation of other immune cells
{{c1::Endocrine}}: distant cells using endocrine system, e.g. hormone secretion into blood like cortisol → inhibition of T cells in thymus → immunodeficiency

{{c1::Ligand-gated ion channels}}: transmembrane ligand binding changes conformation of channel in membrane to open and allow ions to enter/leave cell → depolarization or
hyperpolarization → cellular effects

e.g. neurotransmitter - acetylcholine binds skeletal muscles → receptor channel 
opens → Na+ into cell → depolarization → Ca++ release from sarcoplasmic
reticulum → muscle contraction

{{c1::G-protein coupled receptors}}: transmembrane inactive G proteins activated by ligand binding → dissociated G protein activates effector enzyme → active effector enzyme → increased ionization or phosphorylation → cellular effects
e.g. follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) or thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH)

{{c1::Kinase-linked receptors}}: ligand binding causes transmembrane receptor proteins 
phosphorylated by cytoplasmic kinase → kinase phosphorylation cascade → regulation of gene expression → protein synthesis → cellular effects

e.g. epidermal growth factor, fibroblast growth factor 
Includes intrinsic kinase or kinase-associated receptors, e.g. tyrosine kinase
binding to receptor, getting phosphorylated, then binding kinase

{{c1::Intracellular receptors}}: lipid-soluble (lipophilic) signaling molecules across membrane 
into cell bind cytoplasmic or nuclear receptors → alter gene expression/transcription → protein synthesis → cellular effects
e.g. steroid hormones (estrogen, testosterone) and vitamin D are lipid-soluble with receptors that are ligand-dependent transcription factors that bind DNA

Define the following terms in the context of cell signaling, and diagram their interrelationships: ligand, receptor, kinase, phosphatase, amplification, regulation, G protein, phosphorylation, second messenger, cascade, cell surface receptor, intracellular receptor

-  Ligand (signaling cell) binds receptor (target cell)
-  Kinases phosphorylate (addition of phosphate group), while phosphatases
dephosphorylate
-  Amplification increases signal strength at each step of the signaling pathway
-  Regulation allows for upregulation/downregulation b/c signaling pathways are dynamic
and reversible
-  G protein aka GTP-binding protein act as molecular switches

children.name: F)Introduction to the Principles of Pharmacology

fields: {{c1::Pharmacology}}: study of effects of chemicals on living systems

- Drugs modify physiological processes, not create new processes/effects - Therapeutic window is dose range where one effect of drug predominates over another 
- Drugs result in more than one effect 
- Drugs at high dose are toxic
{{c1::Pharmacokinetics:}} absorption, distribution, biotransformation, excretion of drugs, i.e. how body deals with drug
{{c1::Pharmacodynamics}}: biochemical and physiological effects of drugs and MOA, i.e. how drug affects body
{{c1::Pharmacotherapeutics}}: use of drugs in prevention/treatment of disease
Define the three general mechanisms of drug actions
Deficiency,Excess action,Physiochemical environment
- replacement therapy, e.g. vitamin, thyroxin, insulin, SSRI
chemical antagonist, modified antibodies, or exogenous substances, e.g. beta-blocker b/c too much norepinephrine slows the heart, or naloxone (opioid antagonist) for opioid overdose
specific part of body to be altered, “nonspecific” drugs, e.g. laxatives change characteristics of GI tract to allow more water, or antacid to neutralize acid and treat GERD
Define what it takes for a drug to have affinity for a receptor
Affinity depends on shape, size, charge, atomic composition
Compare and contrast therapeutic index vs therapeutic window.

Therapeutic index is the toxic dose/effective dose = TD50/ED50
- Increased index = safer drug, i.e. larger dose difference between toxic and beneficial is safer 
- Therapeutic window is the dose range between the minimum effective/therapeutic dose and minimum toxic dose 
- Increased window = safer drug b/c increased index 
- Narrow therapeutic index drugs: lithium, phenytoin, carbamazepine, warfarin, cyclosporine, levothyroxine, digoxin, theophylline

Epithelium constitutes a diverse group of tissues that cover all 
body surfaces (e.g. epidermis of skin, intestinal epithelium, 
respiratory epithelium), and line all body cavities and blood 
vessels. An epithelium is made up of an uninterrupted layer of 
cells that both forms a {{c1::barrier}} and {{c2::mediates exchange}}
between two compartments, usually the inside of the body and 
the outside world.

In fact, there are only two types of epithelia that 
do not face the outside world. These are {{c1::endothelium,}} which lines 
all blood vessels and the heart, and {{c2::mesothelium,}} which lines the 
{{c3::pleural}}, pericardial, and {{c4::abdominopelvic cavities}}

Epithelial cells are {{c1::polarized}}: they maintain characteristic nonrandom distributions of organelles, and their plasma membrane is 
differentiated into {{c2::apical, lateral, and basal}} domains with distinct 
protein and lipid compositions.

Describe characteristics that distinguish the four tissue types from each other.
Epithelium,Connective tissue,Muscle,Neural tissue
{{c1::Epithelium}}: covers body surfaces and lines body cavities and blood vessels to form a barrier and mediate exchange (absorption, secretion, excretion)
Ce{{c1::ll types/layers}}: simple or stratified (pseudostratified, transitional for stretching) & squamous, cuboidal, columnar
Non-true epithelium are {{c1::endothelium}} (lines blood vessels and heart) and {{c1::mesothelium}} (lines pleural, pericardial, abdominopelvic cavities)
{{c1::Apical}}: microvilli, cilia (axoneme microtubule core, beat via dynein)
{{c1::Lateral}}: tight junctions, adherens junctions, desmosomes, gap junctions
{{c1::Connective tissue}}: supporting tissues and capsules for mechanical and metabolic support and defense (location for inflammatory responses) with low cell density, high ECM
- ECM composed of ground substance made up of fibers, non-fibrous, and fluid secreted by fibroblasts
{{c1::Type I collagen}}: forms fibrils that combine to form fibers and large bundles synthesized as procollagen by fibroblasts → tropocollagen → normal collagen

- Impairment: requires vit C for synthesis (e.g. scurvy causes 
hemorrhage and impaired wound healing) 
- Locations: fascia, dermis, tendon, lamina propria 
- Organization: loose, dense irregular, dense regular

{{c1::Type III collagen (reticular fibers)}}: small bundles form loose 3D network (reticulum) to support loose connective tissue and provide scaffolding for solid organs, secreted by mesenchymal reticular cells or fibroblastic reticular cells

- Impairment: Ehlers Danlos syndrome - defects in structural 
stability, prone to vessel and organ rupture 
- Locations: liver, lamina propria of hollow organs
{{c1::Elastic fibers}}: for elasticity, synthesized/secreted by fibroblasts and smooth muscle as tropoelastin → assembled to form fibers and sheets

Impairment: requires fibrillin -
 Marfan’s syndrome defect - aorta at risk of aneurysm/rupture
{{c1::Ground substance}}: gel-like for cell migration and regulation of cell differentiation

{{c1::Proteoglycans}}: polymerize to form negatively charged 
glycosaminoglycans (GAGs) which attract water → hydrated gel fills volume, resists compression, provides space for small molecules and cells - Hyaluronan, type of GAG
{{c1::Fibronectin}}: binds integrins to propel cells through CT for cell migration, e.g. inflammation and wound healing
{{c1::Laminin}}: binds integrins and Type IV collagen for integrity of basal lamina

{{c1::Fibroblasts/fibrocytes}}: synthesize ECM molecules, wound healing and
fibrosis, myofibroblast differentiation during wound healing
{{c1::Adipocytes}}: large cells that store and mobilize lipids for energy store

{{c1::Mast cells}}: along small blood vessels for degranulation in response to 
injury or allergens → release histamine, heparin, and proteolytic enzymes → incr. vascular permeability, itching, anaphylaxis
- Cell migration thru leaky walls of post-capillary venules

{{c1::Smooth muscle}}: strengthens hollow organ walls and provides involuntary
(visceral) weak, slow contractions

- Elongated tapered cells with 1 nucleus running parallel to each other, no sarcomeres or striations 
- Regenerative properties via differentiated smooth muscle cells that reenter cell cycle and proliferate (not stem cells)
{{c1::Skeletal muscle}}: multiple fascicles running parallel, highly innervated, surrounded by dense CT providing voluntary rapid, powerful contractions

- Muscle fascicle: multiple long, unbranched myofibers with multiple nuclei along cell periphery 
- Striated cells with sarcomeres (contractile proteins) 
- Regenerative properties via satellite cells (stem cells) activated by damage or intense exercise
{{c1::Cardiac muscle}}: bulk of the heart providing involuntary regular, powerful contractions

- Long individual striated myofibers with sarcomeres organized into 
fascicles 
- Branched myofibers with 1-2 central nuclei connected via intercalated discs
{{c1::Neural tissue:}} Peripheral nerves: axons whose cell bodies are in the CNS or ganglia (cluster of neurons) outside the CNS, made up of nerve fascicles

- CT: endoneurium around each neuron, perineurium up against fascicle surface to form blood-nerve barrier, epineurium around fascicle 
- Schwann cells (glial - support) form myelin sheath with gaps (node of Ranvier)
{{c1::Ganglia}}: nerve cell bodies outside the CNS
{{c1::Dorsal root ganglia}}: for sensory stimuli from periphery into spinal cord
{{c1::Sympathetic ganglia}}: for sympathetic part of autonomic nervous system along spinal column
{{c1::Parasympathetic ganglia}}: within organs they innervate, e.g. digestive tube

{{c1::Skeletal muscle}}: multiple fascicles running parallel, highly innervated, surrounded
by dense CT providing voluntary rapid, powerful contractions

Muscle fascicle: multiple long, unbranched myofibers with multiple nuclei
along cell periphery
Striated cells with sarcomeres (contractile proteins)
 Regenerative properties via satellite cells (stem cells) activated by damage
or intense exercise

{{c1::Cardiac muscle:}} bulk of the heart providing involuntary regular, powerful
contractions

Long individual striated myofibers with sarcomeres organized into
fascicles
Branched myofibers with 1-2 central nuclei connected via intercalated discs
Intercalated discs anchor sarcomeres via AJs (fascia adherens),
intercellular adhesion via desmosomes, rapid electrical and
chemical signal communication via gap junctions - No regenerative properties b/c very few satellite cells
A {{c1::locus}} is the position of a gene on a chromosome.

{{c1::Alleles}} are alternative forms of a gene found 
at the same locus on homologous chromosomes.

{{c1::Homozygotes}} have2 identical alleles at a locus. {{c2::Heterozygotes}} have {{c3::2}} different alleles at a locus. 
{{c4::Hemizygotes}} have only {{c5::1}} allele at a locus

{{c1::Genetic heterogeneity}} is a term used to describe the phenomenon where the same phenotype is 
caused by {{c2::different}} genotypic abnormalities.

{{c1::Allelic heterogeneity}} occurs when the abnormal phenotype 
is caused by {{c2::different}} mutations at the {{c3::same}} locus.

Autosomal {{c1::dominant d}}isorders or traits are those expressed in either the {{c2::heterozygote or
the homozygote}}.
What are the four charactersistic sof autosomal dominant disorders

(1) the phenotype appears in every generation; (2) any 
child of an affected parent has a 50% chance of inheriting the trait; (3) phenotypically normal family

members do not transmit the trait to their children; and (4) males and females are equally likely to 
transmit the phenotype to their offspring of either gender. Male to male transmission is the cardinal 
feature distinguishing autosomal dominant from X-linked traits.
What is the definition for a genetic mutation that impacts multiple organs {{c1::pleiotrophy}}

{{c1::Variable expression}} is said to 
occur when individuals with the same genotype have different phenotypes

{{c1::. Reduced penetrance}} may also be a feature of autosomal dominant conditions. {{c2::Penetrance}} is
an all-or-none phenomenon.That is, one either shows some features of the genotype or none at all.
X-linked disorders are conditions for which the {{c1::locus}} is on the X chromosome
Describe the lyon hypothesis  there are four main principles

In female somatic cells only one X is active. The second X is condensed and is represented as 
the Barr body in interphase cells.
• Inactivation is an early embryonic event.
• The inactive X may be either the paternal or maternal X. Once a particular X is inactivated, all
the clonal descendants of that cell will have the same inactive X.
• The Lyon hypothesis explains dosage compensation and variable expression in
female heterozygotes.

{{c1::Dosage compensation}} refers to the finding that females express only one allele (i.e., one "dose") of 
their X-linked genes, although they actually have two alleles (i.e., two "doses"). This ensures that females 
do not produce twice the gene product of their male counterparts, who have only one allele for X-linked 
genes

What are the six characteristics of x linked recessive inheritance{{c1:: (1) the incidence of the trait is much higher in males than females;}} ({{c2::2) the male 
offspring of carrier females have a 50% chance of being affected and the female offspring have a 50% 
chance of being carriers;}} ({{c3::3) the mutant gene is transmitted from an affected man to all his daughters, who 
are therefore all carriers;}} {{c4::(4) the mutant gene is never transmitted from father to son;}} {{c5::(5) affected males in a 
kindred are related through females; and}} ({{c6::6) heterozygous females are usually unaffected but may show 
variable expression of the condition.}}
Hemophilia A and{{c1:: Duchenne muscular dystrophy (DMD)}} are x linked recessive

four characterisitics of x linked dominant ineritance {{c1::(1) affected males have no affected sons and only 
affected daughters (no normal daughters);}} {{c2::(2) both male and female offspring of heterozygous females 
have a 50% chance of being affected;}} ({{c3::3) for rare phenotypes, affected females are twice as common as 
affected males and usually have milder expression of the phenotype; and}} {{c4::(4) for conditions which are 
prenatal lethal in hemizygous males, the sex ratio of offspring of heterozygous mothers is 2:1 female to 
male, since all affected male conceptuses are spontaneously aborted}}
These two disorders are autosomal recessive {{c1::Tay Sachs and Sickle Cell Anemia }}
